Nigeria’s trade balance rose by 2.50 per cent to hit N831.6bn in the first quarter of 2019 compared to the last quarter of 2018. Report on Foreign Trade in Goods released by the National Bureau of Statistics showed that the favourable trade balance was boosted by increase in both exports and imports. The boost helped total trade increase to N8.24 trillion in the first quarter of 2019, being 2.50 per cent higher compared to the last quarter of 2018 and 7.52 per cent higher relative to the corresponding quarter in 2018. In the first quarter of 2019, Nigeria’s total exports was recorded at N4.54 trillion, which represents a 1.78 per cent rise compared to the fourth quarter of 2018 but a 3.9 per cent fall compared to the first quarter of 2018. Similarly, the value of total imports increased to N3.70 trillion, representing an increase of 3.39 per cent relative to last quarter of 2018 and 29.84 per cent compared with first quarter of 2018. Nigeria’s major traded agricultural products included sesamum seeds, whether or not broken; fermented Nigerian cocoa beans; raw cocoa beans; cashew nuts, in shell; frozen shrimps and prawns; and raw cocoa beans. Nigeria’s major export trading partners included India (16.43%), Spain (10.74%), Netherlands (8.94%), South Africa (7.18%) and France (6.67%) while the major import trading partners included China (26.4%), Swaziland (14.3%), United States (8.8%), India (6.6%), and Netherlands (4.1%).  Nigeria records trade surplus of N1.44tln in Q4 - NBS Nigeria’s export base must be diversified – Expert JUST IN: Foreign trade volume hits N32.26trn in 2018 – NBS Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin